{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"11341d15-f3e7-4b7c-bf47-c7dd32cc8c6b","content":"**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (ships with the .NET SDK). It's the simplest way to capture a CPU profile for .NET 8.\n\n### Steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (if not already)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper analysis)\n\nIf you need kernel-level context (thread scheduling, GC, I/O):\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\nPerfView captures ETW events and gives flame graphs, call trees, and GC stats — more powerful but steeper learning curve.\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for quick triage. Escalate to PerfView if you need OS-level detail.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"183aa2f8-348e-4514-a286-947a4ff2ca2d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about diagnosing a CPU issue on a .NET 8 service running on Windows Server. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I should give a concise, actionable answer.\n\nThe best tool for this is `dotnet-trace` or PerfView. For CPU specifically, `dotnet-trace` with the cpu-sampling profile is the simplest, but PerfView gives richer ETW-based data. Since they have admin access on Windows, PerfView is the gold standard for CPU profiling on Windows.\n\nLet me give a concise recommendation.","outputTokens":440,"requestId":"D800:33DE98:E45583:106AEB0:69F2AFAD"},"id":"5830233b-cee8-4cea-96ae-45dade47189d","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:26:16.143Z","parentId":"bbe4dc3a-2d1b-4eab-a2f6-0b4ed6b6721d"}
